    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-03-30T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-03-30T19:00:00-05:00" n="288"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d288">
                <head>288. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in France</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d288fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 751S.00/3–3059. Secret; Limit Distribution. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_LMJJ1">Looram</persName>, cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BJAJ1">Bovey</persName>, and approved and signed for
                            <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName> by <persName
                            corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName>. Repeated to Tunis, Rabat, and
                        Algiers.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1959-03-30T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 30, 1959—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3624. <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName> called in French Ambassador
                    March 30 to discuss French démarches re US Government contacts with <gloss
                        target="#t_FLN1">FLN</gloss> representatives.<note n="2" xml:id="d288fn2">A
                        memorandum of this conversation is <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>
                    </note> Said established US tradition for Department not close doors to anyone
                    who requested being heard. Moreover it had not been frequent practice receive
                        <gloss target="#t_FLN1">FLN</gloss> and French Embassy kept informed in each
                    instance. However given importance French Government evidently attached this
                    issue, <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName> advised <persName
                        corresp="#p_AH1">Alphand</persName> we would not receive <gloss
                        target="#t_FLN1">FLN</gloss> representatives for time being in Department.
                    This would of course not preclude chance encounters at foreign diplomatic
                    receptions or occasions of this nature. It was emphasized to Ambassador
                    necessity keeping this matter highly confidential in view possibility other
                    foreign governments might cite it as precedent for insisting Department not
                    receive other foreign dissident groups and in view possibility adverse reaction
                    or part certain elements US public and Congress.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_AH1">Alphand</persName> expressed appreciation for this
                    decision. He did not raise question visas for <gloss target="#t_FLN1"
                        >FLN</gloss>, latter’s propaganda activities this country or possibility
                    substantive discussions with <gloss target="#t_FLN1">FLN</gloss> outside
                    Department, either in this country or abroad.</p>
                <p>You may at your discretion advise Foreign Office of position taken with <persName
                        corresp="#p_AH1">Alphand</persName> above, stressing importance this not
                    leak to press or foreign governments.<note n="3" xml:id="d288fn3">In a March 31
                        meeting with <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_CMM1">Couve de Murville</persName> “expressed satisfaction”
                        with this decision, but stated that “the principal trouble” stemmed from the
                        presence of <gloss target="#t_FLN1">FLN</gloss> representatives in the
                        United States. <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName> reiterated that
                        the United States could not deny these individuals visas. (<gloss
                            target="#t_USDel1">USDel</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>/24;
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.,</hi> Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation: Lot
                        64 D 199) <persName corresp="#p_CMM1">Couve de Murville</persName> was in
                        Washington to attend the <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> Ministerial
                        Meeting held April 2–4.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
